
TY  - JOUR
T1  - Inflation and Debt Rollover Under Low Interest Rates
AU  - Miao, Jianjun
AU  - Shen, Zhouxiang
AU  - Su, Dongling
Y1  - 2025/12/01
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12782
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1781
EP  - 1807
VL  - 66
IS  - 5
KW  - debt rollover
KW  - fiscal deficit
KW  - inflation
KW  - new Keynesian
KW  - perpetual youth
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12782
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - ABSTRACT We provide a New Keynesian model with overlapping generations to study the impact of temporary and permanent increases in fiscal deficits financed by debt rollover policy when interest rates are lower than economic growth rates. The debt rollover policy is feasible in the monetary regime but leads to very slow-moving debt. This policy generates persistent inflation for a temporary increase in fiscal deficits, but persistent disinflation for a permanent increase. For social welfare, the debt rollover policy dominates the conventional fiscal rule to finance a temporary increase in fiscal deficits, but it is dominated if the increase is permanent.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - How do Multinationals Impact China's Technology? The Role of Quid Pro Quo Policy and Technology Spillovers
AU  - Ma, Xiao
AU  - Zhang, Yiran
Y1  - 2025/12/01
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.70006
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1933
EP  - 1956
VL  - 66
IS  - 5
KW  - knowledge spillovers
KW  - multinational activities
KW  - technology transfers
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.70006
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - ABSTRACT Using comprehensive patent data, we document: (1) multinational affiliates and their foreign parent firms comprise a significant portion of patents filed in China; and (2) there are subsequent transfers and spillovers of these technologies to domestic firms. Guided by this evidence, we develop a model of multinational production featuring cross-country idea flows, transfers, and spillovers. Quantitatively, we find that without multinational production and knowledge spillovers, the idea stock owned by China would drop by 30%. Furthermore, due to the externalities of multinationals through technology transfers and spillovers, subsidizing multinationals will at most increase real income by 8% in China.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Collateral-Based Monetary Policy: Evidence From China
AU  - Fang, Hanming
AU  - Wang, Yongqin
AU  - Wu, Xian
Y1  - 2025/12/01
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.70012
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1839
EP  - 1881
VL  - 66
IS  - 5
KW  - bond spread
KW  - collateral-based monetary policy
KW  - Medium-Term Lending Facility
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.70012
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - ABSTRACT We exploit the unique institutional features of Chinese bond markets to estimate the causal effect of collateral-based monetary policy on asset prices and the real economy. A policy change allowed certain bonds to be used as collateral for the Medium-Term Lending Facility in the interbank market, while the same bonds in the exchange market remained ineligible. This change reduced the spreads of the newly eligible bonds by 37?53 basis points, or 10%?15% of the average spread in the secondary interbank market, with a strong pass-through rate of 67 to over 100% to the primary interbank market.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Macroeconomic Model of Structural Monetary Policy in China
AU  - Dong, Feng
AU  - Mei, Dongzhou
AU  - Sun, Haoning
Y1  - 2025/12/01
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.70013
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1813
EP  - 1834
VL  - 66
IS  - 5
KW  - China economy
KW  - credit shock
KW  - financial frictions
KW  - SOE–POE asymmetry
KW  - structural monetary policy
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.70013
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - ABSTRACT China's increasing use of structural monetary policy raises questions about its optimal role. This study investigates when and how SMP should be deployed using a multisector DSGE model incorporating distinct financing conditions and intermediary constraints for SOEs and POEs. We find that credit tightening disproportionately raises POE credit spreads, which conventional policy struggles to correct. Credit shocks significantly amplify resource misallocation and necessitate active SMP to address these specific distortions, stabilize the economy, and mitigate associated welfare losses. Our findings indicate that the justification for SMP is strongest when credit shocks significantly interact with underlying financial asymmetries between sectors.
ER  - 

